00:20:38.959 --> 00:20:43.280
Because a lot of projects today are kind of making up their – well, not making up their

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:49.359
own, but they're slightly changing up the definition of things when they write it in

00:20:49.359 --> 00:20:54.880
protocols or a data reviewer's guide or whatever it is that we're handing over to authorities.

00:20:54.880 --> 00:20:59.119
So, it's to build a system to manage all of that.

00:20:59.119 --> 00:21:03.119
And for us, it will be API calls internally.

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:14.000
We have – the same way we have a master model of our metadata for, for instance,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:21.199
STDM study data and analysis data, we also have a master model of all the metadata

00:21:21.199 --> 00:21:26.560
datasets that go into producing both those datasets, but also tables, figures, and listings.

00:21:27.199 --> 00:21:36.239
So, I mean, we're betting really hard on having a fully metadata-driven pipeline

00:21:38.160 --> 00:21:41.199
to the extent possible that we can do it.

00:21:41.199 --> 00:21:42.079
Thank you.

00:21:42.079 --> 00:21:45.359
I'm going to jump over to a few of the anonymous questions, too.

00:21:45.359 --> 00:21:50.560
And one was, could Ari share a bit about how he got into the pharma industry?

00:21:51.599 --> 00:21:51.839
Yes.

00:21:51.839 --> 00:21:55.359
So, as I said, I mean, my background was in mathematics.

00:21:55.359 --> 00:22:00.160
I was doing topology and high-dimensional geometry.

00:22:01.599 --> 00:22:08.800
And at some point during the master's part of my education, I was thinking, who needs

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:10.319
this out in the real world?

00:22:12.160 --> 00:22:18.079
So, I kind of shifted towards doing more statistics stuff, doing more programming.

00:22:19.439 --> 00:22:24.560
And I kind of learned that high-dimensional geometry is not that different from

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.079
n-dimensional feature spaces.

00:22:28.079 --> 00:22:31.760
And I got really caught up in learning about machine learning.

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:39.359
And I did my master's thesis in prediction modeling on MRI data.

00:22:40.479 --> 00:22:50.800
So, I was really intrigued by that intersection between medicine and technology.

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:53.599
Like, what could you do in that field?

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:59.920
So, I was looking for places where I could explore that more.

00:23:00.560 --> 00:23:05.520
At that time, Siemens were like the one creating all the MRI machines.

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:12.239
But there's, I don't think there's Siemens here in Denmark, where I live.

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:19.439
So, and I ended up applying for a job at Novo at that time.

00:23:20.079 --> 00:23:27.359
And so, I started here straight out of university and haven't left since.

00:23:28.319 --> 00:23:28.959
That's great.

00:23:28.959 --> 00:23:29.359
Thank you.

00:23:31.359 --> 00:23:32.239
Okay, let's see.

00:23:32.239 --> 00:23:34.719
I'll jump over to Mike.

00:23:34.719 --> 00:23:36.959
I saw you asked a question earlier in the chat.

00:23:36.959 --> 00:23:38.160
You want to jump in here next?

00:23:38.160 --> 00:23:40.560
I need to remind myself what the question was.

00:23:40.560 --> 00:23:41.040
Apologies.

00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:48.719
So, I saw a really interesting presentation from Novo Nordisk about the, you know,

00:23:48.719 --> 00:23:52.719
there's essentially a pharmaverse of R packages that you're using.

00:23:54.079 --> 00:23:57.520
And you have packages for everything, basically, which is amazing.

00:23:57.520 --> 00:24:04.000
So, are those packages developed, like, from scratch within Novo?

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.199
Or are those kind of Novo wrappers around other things?

00:24:07.199 --> 00:24:14.400
So, they're primarily wrappers around, like, tidyverse stuff.

00:24:15.199 --> 00:24:21.359
Because there are internal standards to pretty much anything you could think of

00:24:21.359 --> 00:24:22.719
that there is a standard for.

00:24:22.719 --> 00:24:30.719
So, and some of them are to make it possible to work with R within our environment,

00:24:30.719 --> 00:24:33.439
like the way we store data, the way we export things.

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:39.199
And I said, like, utility functions to work with Azure DevOps, to work with Git,

00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:45.920
to work with, to all these different systems that we have internally.

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:50.880
Some of them, can you still hear me all right?

00:24:52.400 --> 00:24:57.119
Yes, I think it froze for a second on my end, but I could hear you the whole time.

00:24:57.119 --> 00:24:57.359
Okay.

00:24:59.359 --> 00:25:08.479
So, some of it is, like, layering on top of these metadata to do things smarter.

00:25:09.280 --> 00:25:17.040
Some of it is building, like, a package for creating tables that are specific to the

00:25:17.040 --> 00:25:19.359
Novo way of styling tables and so on.

00:25:19.359 --> 00:25:30.560
So, but one thing that kind of has kind of catched up to us is they were developed without,

00:25:32.719 --> 00:25:36.400
like, looking too much to the open source world.

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:43.119
So, now when we actually want to do more with Farmiverse, where multiple companies are working,

00:25:43.119 --> 00:25:51.040
it's really hard to separate, like, the Novo part and, like, the real functionality of the package.

00:25:51.040 --> 00:25:53.040
So, we're working on that now.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:01.280
It's an interesting design issue then, you know, because I can understand that building wrappers

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:05.839
on existing things to tailor it for your needs is a really neat way of doing things.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:10.319
But as you say, it kind of then locks you into a particular way of working that maybe,

00:26:10.880 --> 00:26:12.400
you know, has problems down the line.

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:13.839
So, there are probably pros and cons, right?

00:26:14.719 --> 00:26:15.280
Exactly.

00:26:16.079 --> 00:26:23.280
And we do, and I mean, there's also, like, in recent years, so many companies have opened up

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:28.959
much more to talk about how they're actually solving things, and we're also doing that as well.

00:26:28.959 --> 00:26:34.000
And we really want to contribute to kind of keeping those lines open.

00:26:34.719 --> 00:26:39.839
So, we're definitely trying to pivot some of our packages,

00:26:39.839 --> 00:26:44.160
either kind of committing to some of the open source packages that are there,

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:50.079
or pivoting our packages and kind of see if they can get into the open source world.

00:26:50.079 --> 00:26:51.520
Amanda, I see you raised your hand.

00:26:51.520 --> 00:26:52.479
Do you want to jump in here?

00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:54.239
Hi, yeah.

00:26:54.800 --> 00:27:00.560
So, I'm a little bit curious about the transition Novo Nordisk made.

00:27:01.520 --> 00:27:04.400
Our, I guess there's two parts to this question.

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:10.079
The first is, you know, during that trying to prove that, you know,

00:27:10.079 --> 00:27:14.000
the Pharmaverse or using R was just as good as SAS programming.

00:27:15.040 --> 00:27:19.599
How did you have, like, you know, I know there's always a second reader on the data.

00:27:19.599 --> 00:27:24.959
So, did you have one person using R and the other person using SAS, or how did that go?

00:27:24.959 --> 00:27:30.239
And then the other question I have is, you know, I've seen some reports

00:27:30.800 --> 00:27:34.079
the R and SAS data coming back just slightly different.

00:27:34.079 --> 00:27:37.520
Nothing that would change a decision or anything, but just slightly different.

00:27:38.959 --> 00:27:44.239
So, how do you sort of address that as you're, like, sort of mid-transition here?

00:27:44.239 --> 00:27:47.760
I mean, to speak to your first question.

00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:56.719
So, our primary goal has not been to, like, replace SAS with R.

00:27:56.719 --> 00:28:01.839
I mean, we are really aiming for a much more, like, language agnostic world

00:28:01.839 --> 00:28:05.520
where programmers use the language that they're most comfortable with.

00:28:06.640 --> 00:28:12.239
In terms of, like, getting it into the organization and having people using it,

00:28:13.199 --> 00:28:18.560
we started out, like, what we really wanted to prove was that it was possible to, like,

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:24.640
make a real deliverable with R, where we make the tables and figures in R.

00:28:25.359 --> 00:28:32.560
So, there we did the actual deliverable in R, and we did the parallel programming in SAS

00:28:32.560 --> 00:28:39.520
to make sure that it is what we would expect to get in SAS as well.

00:28:40.079 --> 00:28:45.839
And then down the line, I mean, I remember seeing one of my good peers,

00:28:45.839 --> 00:28:53.119
Michael Rimler from GSK, talking about their program called R for validation,

00:28:53.119 --> 00:28:59.520
where they were really rolling out that everybody was allowed to use R for validation.

00:28:59.520 --> 00:29:07.439
And I think, like, building on top of that, we thought that, well, I mean,

00:29:07.439 --> 00:29:12.479
they're already using it for validation, so why not try to use it in production?

00:29:13.119 --> 00:29:14.560
Like, on a very small scale.

00:29:15.520 --> 00:29:24.000
And now, today, we have, I mean, all kinds of mixtures of how people are approaching it.

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:33.119
Whether they're doing the primary program in SAS and R is not that important anymore,

00:29:33.119 --> 00:29:39.760
because we kind of built up an environment that supports, like, a multilingual execution.

00:29:40.719 --> 00:29:44.479
And now I can remember your second question. Can you repeat that again?

00:29:45.439 --> 00:29:49.199
Mostly about how, you know, because there are small differences in the

00:29:49.199 --> 00:29:51.599
numerical algorithm, you know, like, how is that addressed?

00:29:52.319 --> 00:29:58.880
Yeah. So, I mean, so we expect that there is a difference.

00:29:58.880 --> 00:30:08.079
So, and many of the, like, compare packages that's out there, you can set a criterion on how

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:13.599
to which decimal places should the numbers align.

00:30:14.719 --> 00:30:22.079
And there's always, like, when you're storing floating point integers, there will always be,

00:30:22.079 --> 00:30:27.280
like, a small difference even with, like, the same number within the same system.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:37.119
And I think what we have really been preaching internally is that we really try to preach,

00:30:37.119 --> 00:30:43.280
like, conclusions over numbers. So, of course, if you see something that's totally off,

00:30:44.079 --> 00:30:50.560
you're going to investigate what's happened there. But that when we use and kind of set

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:56.719
these two systems up against each other, are we still looking at the same conclusions for

00:30:58.319 --> 00:31:04.479
these adverse events or this lab parameter and so on? So, that's been our kind of take on it.

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:14.079
Thank you. Jared, I see you had asked a question. One had a star, so maybe I'll start reading. And

00:31:14.079 --> 00:31:19.520
if you want to jump in, I'll look to see if you unmute. But Jared said, definitely interested in

00:31:19.520 --> 00:31:26.079
knowing more about how you pitched to your upper management to use Shiny apps. And Jared said,

00:31:26.079 --> 00:31:32.479
mainly I get pushback because of validation concerns on doing that versus the standard

00:31:32.479 --> 00:31:48.160
200-page PDF files. Yeah. I think I would say, luckily, our management have been very open to,

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:56.479
like, it's almost expected that you try and solve problems in a new way. And that's kind of what

00:31:56.479 --> 00:32:03.920
we've been raised with here. At least, I've been raised with it here. So, of course, there are a

00:32:03.920 --> 00:32:10.400
lot of technical aspects around that. But we kind of did the same thing that you would do with maybe

00:32:10.959 --> 00:32:15.839
another innovation product is that you would talk with the people who are supposed to use it. And

00:32:18.640 --> 00:32:23.199
most of them said that it was a really good idea. And then we said to our management,

00:32:23.199 --> 00:32:30.079
like, everybody thinks this is a great idea, right? And we think we have the skills to build

00:32:30.079 --> 00:32:37.040
it. And, of course, one good thing is it's always good to apply a little bit of action on an idea

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:43.040
before you go searching for opinions because opinions can quickly kind of hold you back.

00:32:44.079 --> 00:32:51.839
And we had already applied some actions, like built something around it. And so, you're kind

00:32:51.839 --> 00:32:59.280
of coming up with something that they almost, at least we're trying to get into a scenario where

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:04.719
they can't say no, or at least that, like, can we test this out in one or two trials?

00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:14.319
And then you make sure that, like, all of the downstream processes around this, I mean,

00:33:14.319 --> 00:33:18.000
we're still, like, in compliance with standards. We're still, like,

00:33:18.959 --> 00:33:26.560
able to deliver everything we're supposed to do. And now, hopefully, people would be a lot happier.

00:33:26.560 --> 00:33:31.839
And now also, like, CO2, right? We really want to save some trees as well.

00:33:34.239 --> 00:33:40.959
So, that's been a major selling point for us in terms of Shiny apps. And then also,

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:46.959
another thing that I think most companies say today is that they really want to be

00:33:48.079 --> 00:33:54.719
data-driven, right? And if you want to hold people to the word, I think, like, our community is

00:33:54.719 --> 00:34:03.040
probably one of the parts of the organization that have, like, the most enabling power to give

00:34:03.520 --> 00:34:11.199
to other people who doesn't necessarily have data scientist skills. I think that's, like,

00:34:11.199 --> 00:34:17.040
if you can make somebody higher up in the organization, realize that you can make

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:24.879
so many people do their job in a much more simple way just by going into a Shiny app,

00:34:24.879 --> 00:34:30.959
or maybe even just, like, looking at automated reports on a connector, I mean, what be it,

00:34:31.600 --> 00:34:39.600
that you can enable so many people just by doing that. So, yeah, that's been our,

00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:44.479
kind of, selling point of trying to get all of this into our processes.

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:50.399
Love that. Thank you. Hugh, I see you had a question in the chat. Want to jump in here?

00:34:51.439 --> 00:34:58.000
Hi, Agus. So, my background is in mathematics, and I'm now moving into bioscience. So,

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:01.439
I'm currently doing my PhD, and I'm going to finish in a couple years, and industry just

00:35:01.439 --> 00:35:07.360
seems like this massive unknown, where, as an academic, I don't really know what is wanted.

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:11.840
Do you have any advice for, like, things to learn or technologies to learn to make yourself

00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:17.280
more competitive in that environment, and specifically in bioscience? Sorry.

00:35:17.280 --> 00:35:24.479
Yeah, I think, I mean, now I can only really speak for my own company. I think there are,

00:35:24.479 --> 00:35:30.719
of course, like, some technologies that we're moving more towards. I mean, so, if you know,

00:35:32.080 --> 00:35:39.520
like, any of the open source languages, like, do you have, I mean, recently,

00:35:40.800 --> 00:35:45.760
when we have candidates, we also look, I mean, are they on GitHub? Like, have they

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:53.840
done something interesting? Do they, can they, like, display a passion for what they're doing,

00:35:53.840 --> 00:36:00.399
and for us now, we're also putting it in our job ads that it's almost more important that you are,

00:36:00.399 --> 00:36:07.040
like, willing to learn new stuff. Of course, there are some jobs, also in the farm industry,

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:13.520
where you have to have a specific degree to do that job, but, for instance, for development

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:20.479
jobs, we're looking much more into that. Like, you have a passion for doing it, we can see that

00:36:20.479 --> 00:36:28.719
you have done it before, and when we speak with you, you know your way around, like,

00:36:28.719 --> 00:36:34.560
for instance, package development, and which packages you use to do package development.

00:36:36.159 --> 00:36:44.000
So, I think it's a much more, now, a display of interest. So, I think a lot of companies today do

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:56.239
these, like, interview questions or exercises that you do before, and, like, if you're applying

00:36:56.239 --> 00:37:03.360
at a pharmaceutical company, then, like, ask about, like, the disease that you're, maybe you've gotten

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:09.679
some data on some disease, like, what does this mean? What, like, show that you're interested in

00:37:10.639 --> 00:37:22.399
in what it is that they are trying to do in pharma? But, I mean, keeping up with technology

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:27.439
is a really good thing to have on your resume.

00:37:28.639 --> 00:37:36.879
Thank you. Rebecca, I see you mentioned you had a niche question, but I feel like this could be

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:42.080
a good audience to throw that out there, too. So, you want to jump in here?

00:37:42.080 --> 00:37:47.199
Oh, you're super kind. I wasn't going to try to bug the whole group, but I'm in search of someone

00:37:47.199 --> 00:37:55.199
who has any experience with SAS Viya and our interoperability. Yeah, anyway, it's pretty niche,

00:37:55.199 --> 00:38:01.040
so if it doesn't exist, but in the conversation of the agnostic wild west, I was curious if anyone

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:08.800
has that experience. Yeah. Unfortunately, we don't have SAS Viya. I did see that you also

00:38:08.800 --> 00:38:16.399
posted on the farmer's slide, which is great. No, no, I think it's great. I do know, like, some of

00:38:16.399 --> 00:38:26.560
the other Danish pharmaceutical companies use SAS Viya. Maybe I could try and get somebody into

00:38:27.040 --> 00:38:33.439
that Slack channel to share any experience with that. Yeah, I would love that. I'm coming from a

00:38:33.439 --> 00:38:39.360
mostly SAS forward organization, but as currently 100% R user and trying to help people who want to

00:38:39.360 --> 00:38:45.840
use both is my use case, since I think we've already carved out the people who are willing

00:38:45.840 --> 00:38:52.239
to already commit to 100% R. I'm trying to help those who want to use both. So, thank you. I'm

00:38:52.239 --> 00:38:59.040
enjoying this a lot. I'm going to jump back to the conversation about packages for a second here.

00:38:59.040 --> 00:39:03.919
I saw there was a Slido question that said, I'm curious from Mari's experience of writing

00:39:03.919 --> 00:39:09.520
packages, when would it be considered overkill to create a package and when is it justified?

00:39:10.560 --> 00:39:19.439
Well, I mean, it depends on whether, so I mean, of course, now I'm sitting in an organization

00:39:19.439 --> 00:39:25.040
where you know that a lot of people are doing the same exact thing, but maybe just a little bit

00:39:25.040 --> 00:39:31.600
different than you are. So, most of the things that we do every day is something that at least 200

00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:38.879
other people are doing. And that's a really strong rationale for just making

00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:46.159
a package around working specifically with tables or Git or repos and so on.

00:39:46.800 --> 00:39:57.280
But if you're working for yourself or in a small group, like my wife is a PhD

00:39:57.280 --> 00:40:03.520
student currently and has also done a small clinical trial, and you kind of quickly

00:40:03.520 --> 00:40:10.159
learn that you can actually gain so much from setting up functions for yourself to kind of

00:40:10.159 --> 00:40:17.439
repeat tasks over and over again, to read in small data sets or to format something that you

00:40:17.439 --> 00:40:26.719
want to output later on. So, I think there's probably not a package too small if somebody

00:40:26.719 --> 00:40:34.879
benefits from it, and especially yourself. But in our case, it's pretty easy to know when you're

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:42.159
supposed to do a package. Most things, and also kind of referring to a comment before,

00:40:42.159 --> 00:40:47.040
most things end up in a package because we expect that many people will use them.

00:40:48.239 --> 00:40:55.760
How are you actually helping share those packages across the organization or helping

00:40:55.760 --> 00:41:02.879
share what other people are doing in different teams so work doesn't, I guess, get duplicated?

00:41:02.879 --> 00:41:08.000
Do you have community groups? Yeah. So, one thing that was running,

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:15.360
and I think it's still running, is we had this initiative called Radar, where everybody could

00:41:15.360 --> 00:41:24.239
post ideas to not just code development, but process development, or let's get new coffee

00:41:24.239 --> 00:41:30.000
in the coffee machine, or whenever people start, they should get a water bottle now.

00:41:30.639 --> 00:41:40.080
So, all these different things. In terms of code development, moving into Azure DevOps has been a

00:41:40.080 --> 00:41:49.120
way for us to also, first of all, make all of that work visible. So, before, I couldn't necessarily

00:41:49.120 --> 00:41:57.439
see the code and programs from another project, and we tried to really open up and make all of

00:41:57.439 --> 00:42:05.120
that work visible and kind of in a help yourself way, where if I want to see what other people are

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:09.520
doing, I can just now see all of their code, and it's the same way with the package development,

00:42:09.520 --> 00:42:15.280
now that all of that development and organizational development is also

00:42:15.280 --> 00:42:22.000
available for everybody to see. So, that's the way we've done it, yeah.

00:42:22.399 --> 00:42:29.760
Thank you. George, I see you had asked a question a bit earlier about Shiny. Do you want to jump in?

00:42:30.639 --> 00:42:38.000
And I think the question was, do you see, let me just jump back, I think it's, do you see Python

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:42.560
for Shiny as something you would use for your use case in the future, or now?

00:42:43.040 --> 00:42:52.479
I think there will probably, so I'm not that well versed in Python, but I can see,

00:42:54.479 --> 00:43:02.479
I mean, there definitely will be some use cases for Python for us as well, but a lot of the stuff,

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:10.560
like now we have like a huge SAS infrastructure, and now we also build a huge R infrastructure,

00:43:10.560 --> 00:43:17.600
and now when we're starting out with Python, I mean, like you have the reticulate package,

00:43:17.600 --> 00:43:22.560
and you have so much like interoperability between R and Python, that there might be

00:43:23.360 --> 00:43:32.639
many things that where you either use like the Plumber API or reticulate to kind of

00:43:32.639 --> 00:43:38.560
use the best thing of those languages, so not even if you were to at some point in the future

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:44.639
do a full trial in Python, like you would maybe just call some of the R infrastructure

